WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.290 --> 00:00:08.440
Hello, everyone and welcome
to the environment forum

00:00:08.440 --> 00:00:11.330
at the Mahindra
Humanities Center.

00:00:11.330 --> 00:00:14.440
I'm Ian Miller, co-convener
of the forum with Robin Kelce,

00:00:14.440 --> 00:00:17.500
a professor of photography and
Dean of Arts and Humanities

00:00:17.500 --> 00:00:19.900
here at Harvard.

00:00:19.900 --> 00:00:23.282
This is the final event
of ours for the semester.

00:00:23.282 --> 00:00:25.740
We'll continue in the spring
with a set of exciting events,

00:00:25.740 --> 00:00:27.466
always exciting events
here at the forum,

00:00:27.466 --> 00:00:28.840
but these are
particularly great.

00:00:28.840 --> 00:00:32.490
I'm excited to welcome these
two scholars to campus.

00:00:32.490 --> 00:00:35.820
The first is a discussion with
a historian of science Deborah

00:00:35.820 --> 00:00:40.230
Cohen from Yale, recently
moved from Barnard, on the uses

00:00:40.230 --> 00:00:44.010
and abuses of historical
thinking in the climate change

00:00:44.010 --> 00:00:48.480
debate and in the manufacture
of climate knowledge.

00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:52.050
And then second, we'll
have a very welcome visit

00:00:52.050 --> 00:00:54.690
from a familiar figure
here at Harvard,

00:00:54.690 --> 00:00:56.790
the eminent
psychiatrist Robert J.

00:00:56.790 --> 00:01:00.270
Lifton, who has turned
his gaze from the causes

00:01:00.270 --> 00:01:03.120
and costs of conflict
and violence issues

00:01:03.120 --> 00:01:05.700
that he's been dealing with
since he was involved in the US

00:01:05.700 --> 00:01:09.300
occupation of Japan in
the immediate aftermath

00:01:09.300 --> 00:01:13.740
of the Second World War, to
questions of climate change

00:01:13.740 --> 00:01:15.630
and environmental damage.

00:01:15.630 --> 00:01:18.930
It promises to be a terrific
lineup for the spring.

00:01:18.930 --> 00:01:21.090
And it would not be
possible, I have to say,

00:01:21.090 --> 00:01:24.810
I'm very happy to say,
without the unwavering support

00:01:24.810 --> 00:01:26.890
of the Mahindra Center.

00:01:26.890 --> 00:01:30.340
I'd like to begin by thanking
Homi Bhabha, director

00:01:30.340 --> 00:01:34.060
of the center, Steve
Beale, and Sarah Raiser,

00:01:34.060 --> 00:01:36.700
as well as the full
staff at the center.

00:01:36.700 --> 00:01:38.470
You make all of this possible.

00:01:38.470 --> 00:01:40.180
You bring all of us together.

00:01:40.180 --> 00:01:42.250
And it's somehow invisible,
because you do it

00:01:42.250 --> 00:01:44.020
so well each and every time.

00:01:44.020 --> 00:01:47.215
Thank you very much.

00:01:47.215 --> 00:01:49.340
I'm also grateful to all
of you for joining us here

00:01:49.340 --> 00:01:49.881
at the forum.

00:01:49.881 --> 00:01:52.460
I'm absolutely delighted
with the turnout.

00:01:52.460 --> 00:01:54.650
I thought it's
raining, the climate

00:01:54.650 --> 00:01:57.366
has impacted our
talk about climate.

00:01:57.366 --> 00:01:58.490
No one is going to show up.

00:01:58.490 --> 00:02:00.620
And here we are, almost
overflowing the room.

00:02:00.620 --> 00:02:01.400
It's just perfect.

00:02:01.400 --> 00:02:05.060
Thank you for joining us on
a cold, rainy night for what

00:02:05.060 --> 00:02:08.000
promises to be a warm
and engaging talk.

00:02:12.980 --> 00:02:15.260
I'm also grateful
to, or I'd like--

00:02:15.260 --> 00:02:17.420
I'm pleased to introduce
tonight's, excuse me,

00:02:17.420 --> 00:02:20.600
to introduce our
work in this series

00:02:20.600 --> 00:02:24.740
as well as to welcome Professor
Michael Puett, who will join us

00:02:24.740 --> 00:02:26.850
for the Q&amp;A following the talk.

00:02:26.850 --> 00:02:30.310
It was kindly agreed to
introduce tonight's speaker,

00:02:30.310 --> 00:02:31.280
Prasenjit Duara.

00:02:35.400 --> 00:02:37.260
Prasenjit joins us from
Duke, and he's here

00:02:37.260 --> 00:02:39.330
to talk about issues
related to his most

00:02:39.330 --> 00:02:42.480
recent book, The Crisis
of Global Modernity, Asian

00:02:42.480 --> 00:02:43.560
Traditions.

00:02:43.560 --> 00:02:45.240
And I have to
shill for the book,

00:02:45.240 --> 00:02:46.590
because it's a wonderful book.

00:02:46.590 --> 00:02:47.100
Pick it up.

00:02:47.100 --> 00:02:50.040
It's incredibly provocative,
and a great read.

00:02:50.040 --> 00:02:53.430
The Crisis of Global
Modernity, Asian Traditions

00:02:53.430 --> 00:02:55.410
and a Sustainable Future.

00:02:55.410 --> 00:03:00.190
Now, to my eye, the purpose
of the forum is fairly simple.

00:03:00.190 --> 00:03:02.010
It's not all that complicated.

00:03:02.010 --> 00:03:03.720
Our work is, at
the end of the day,

00:03:03.720 --> 00:03:05.970
an effort to situate
the humanities

00:03:05.970 --> 00:03:10.530
and the social sciences
in the natural world.

00:03:10.530 --> 00:03:14.220
I emphasize the
proposition because it's

00:03:14.220 --> 00:03:17.550
meant to carry a double
meaning in this case,

00:03:17.550 --> 00:03:19.890
signaling both the immersion--

00:03:19.890 --> 00:03:23.480
thank you, I saw
that that moved.

00:03:23.480 --> 00:03:27.800
Signaling both the
immersion of our work

00:03:27.800 --> 00:03:30.770
as humans into an
encompassing material world,

00:03:30.770 --> 00:03:33.320
a kind of ecological
embeddedness that is sometimes

00:03:33.320 --> 00:03:37.880
lost in our focus on the
realm of ideas and texts.

00:03:37.880 --> 00:03:41.030
And second, the
recognition that work

00:03:41.030 --> 00:03:44.150
in these fields from the
arts and fiction making

00:03:44.150 --> 00:03:47.120
to history and the
social sciences

00:03:47.120 --> 00:03:49.690
offers crucial
resources as we struggle

00:03:49.690 --> 00:03:51.860
to come to terms with the
reality of our changing

00:03:51.860 --> 00:03:55.310
climate and our changing world.

00:03:55.310 --> 00:03:56.896
Now, it seems that
lately many of us

00:03:56.896 --> 00:03:58.520
want to see the first
of these meanings

00:03:58.520 --> 00:04:00.980
as more radical, more
interesting, more cutting edge.

00:04:00.980 --> 00:04:04.910
Frankly, to use the term that
my graduate advisor used to use,

00:04:04.910 --> 00:04:07.820
sexier intellectually, right?

00:04:07.820 --> 00:04:09.950
The material turn, and
the new materialism

00:04:09.950 --> 00:04:11.600
seem to be everywhere
these days.

00:04:11.600 --> 00:04:15.590
These days, ubiquitous
phrases used

00:04:15.590 --> 00:04:18.800
in ways that signal a
sea change in how we are

00:04:18.800 --> 00:04:20.880
trying to think as scholars.

00:04:20.880 --> 00:04:23.660
I sit on the board for a
nationally competitive graduate

00:04:23.660 --> 00:04:24.950
fellowship down in New York.

00:04:24.950 --> 00:04:25.909
I go down every year.

00:04:25.909 --> 00:04:28.450
And it's a signal of the kind
of durability and applicability

00:04:28.450 --> 00:04:31.290
and kind of trendiness
of this term,

00:04:31.290 --> 00:04:33.710
it turns out that
something like 60%

00:04:33.710 --> 00:04:36.930
of the finalist applications
for the fellowship last year

00:04:36.930 --> 00:04:38.870
used the term entanglement.

00:04:38.870 --> 00:04:41.480
Meant to use-- signal
this embeddedness,

00:04:41.480 --> 00:04:43.010
this material term.

00:04:43.010 --> 00:04:44.900
It's become the new
buzzword of our age,

00:04:44.900 --> 00:04:46.940
it seems like, the way
discourse was when I was

00:04:46.940 --> 00:04:48.950
a grad student in the 1980s.

00:04:48.950 --> 00:04:50.480
We all read
Foucault, we were all

00:04:50.480 --> 00:04:51.950
engaged in the cultural turn.

00:04:51.950 --> 00:04:56.030
Now, we're turning back to
the material world, it seems.

00:04:56.030 --> 00:04:58.490
It's everywhere in
humanistic discourse.

00:04:58.490 --> 00:05:00.500
We can see them and
see that in fairly

00:05:00.500 --> 00:05:02.690
theoretical or philosophical
ways, and a growing

00:05:02.690 --> 00:05:06.050
body of work, critical work
in particular, on ontology,

00:05:06.050 --> 00:05:08.210
the so-called ontological turn.

00:05:08.210 --> 00:05:09.980
And in a renewed
sense of urgency

00:05:09.980 --> 00:05:11.570
around more
traditional questions,

00:05:11.570 --> 00:05:14.660
such as agency, now
distributed in a way

00:05:14.660 --> 00:05:17.810
it was not in our
writing space and place,

00:05:17.810 --> 00:05:20.600
in a richer ecological sense.

00:05:20.600 --> 00:05:23.330
In more immediate
and apparent efforts,

00:05:23.330 --> 00:05:29.830
it's there in such efforts
as our work on book history

00:05:29.830 --> 00:05:34.040
here at Harvard, practiced by
Anne Blair, Bob Darnton, Leah

00:05:34.040 --> 00:05:35.480
Price, and others
here on campus.

00:05:35.480 --> 00:05:38.240
Scholarly work has
never been immaterial,

00:05:38.240 --> 00:05:42.170
these folks remind us, not in
the ways we like to pretend.

00:05:42.170 --> 00:05:44.720
They show us that
the history of ideas

00:05:44.720 --> 00:05:46.670
is also a history of technology.

00:05:46.670 --> 00:05:49.580
In this case, one
especially useful, portable,

00:05:49.580 --> 00:05:51.380
and durable technology.

00:05:51.380 --> 00:05:52.770
The book.

00:05:52.770 --> 00:05:53.940
We see it everywhere.

00:05:53.940 --> 00:05:56.420
And we see op eds
now in the Atlantic,

00:05:56.420 --> 00:05:58.970
the Washington Post, the
New York Times telling us it

00:05:58.970 --> 00:06:01.210
won't go away.

00:06:01.210 --> 00:06:04.690
Now, lately I sometimes
think that the second aspect

00:06:04.690 --> 00:06:08.080
of our mission, the
more commonplace aspect,

00:06:08.080 --> 00:06:10.150
is more challenging.

00:06:10.150 --> 00:06:11.780
The material turn is underway.

00:06:11.780 --> 00:06:13.870
It has momentum, as
is evident in the work

00:06:13.870 --> 00:06:15.370
of those brilliant
graduate students

00:06:15.370 --> 00:06:18.400
who are cranking out grant
applications every fall.

00:06:18.400 --> 00:06:19.870
We see it in our
work, we hear it

00:06:19.870 --> 00:06:23.500
in the questions that come from
our students in our classrooms.

00:06:23.500 --> 00:06:27.490
But what about the uses of
the humanistic tradition?

00:06:27.490 --> 00:06:29.710
As we struggle to come to
terms with our changing

00:06:29.710 --> 00:06:33.070
global climate, how can
the deep traditions, and I

00:06:33.070 --> 00:06:35.500
use that word advisedly
and technically,

00:06:35.500 --> 00:06:39.940
the deep traditions, legacies,
histories and cultures

00:06:39.940 --> 00:06:43.900
enshrined in literate
canons from around the world

00:06:43.900 --> 00:06:47.840
help us to understand and act
in this particular moment?

00:06:47.840 --> 00:06:50.840
How our history in the
deep past, useful today.

00:06:50.840 --> 00:06:54.670
How can we write, as Homi said
in his eloquent introduction

00:06:54.670 --> 00:06:58.480
to our forum hosting
Naomi Oreskes,

00:06:58.480 --> 00:07:01.960
how can we learn to write
in the first person,

00:07:01.960 --> 00:07:04.180
in specific and
personally meaningful

00:07:04.180 --> 00:07:07.150
ways about forces
that so far exceed

00:07:07.150 --> 00:07:11.290
our individual capacity
for representation or even

00:07:11.290 --> 00:07:12.940
comprehension?

00:07:12.940 --> 00:07:17.050
Forces and dynamics such
as global climate change.

00:07:17.050 --> 00:07:20.200
What is the role of the
humanities and scholars

00:07:20.200 --> 00:07:23.730
who practice the humanities
in such a moment?

00:07:23.730 --> 00:07:29.150
Few places, perhaps no
place, offers a greater depth

00:07:29.150 --> 00:07:33.230
of intellectual resources,
defined here as millennia,

00:07:33.230 --> 00:07:37.260
of literate culture with which
to confront these questions

00:07:37.260 --> 00:07:43.400
than China and East Asia, the
locus of this evening's forum.

00:07:43.400 --> 00:07:46.130
And it's difficult to imagine
two scholars who are better

00:07:46.130 --> 00:07:50.150
suited to usher us into
that deep past than Michael

00:07:50.150 --> 00:07:53.120
Puett and Prasenjit Duara.

00:07:53.120 --> 00:07:57.110
Michael will introduce Professor
Duara and this evening's talk,

00:07:57.110 --> 00:08:01.490
but I'm absolutely delighted
to be able to introduce him

00:08:01.490 --> 00:08:03.470
this evening.

00:08:03.470 --> 00:08:06.050
Michael is Walter C. Climb,
professor of Chinese history

00:08:06.050 --> 00:08:09.410
and anthropology here at
Harvard, and the author,

00:08:09.410 --> 00:08:14.090
co-author, editor, and co-editor
of four extremely well-received

00:08:14.090 --> 00:08:17.210
books, with another
quickly on the way.

00:08:17.210 --> 00:08:19.130
But he's probably
best known at Harvard

00:08:19.130 --> 00:08:22.520
as simply one of the best
teachers this school has ever

00:08:22.520 --> 00:08:23.780
seen.

00:08:23.780 --> 00:08:26.840
Michael is a genius
in the classroom.

00:08:26.840 --> 00:08:30.440
If you haven't watched him
teach, sneak into the back

00:08:30.440 --> 00:08:31.460
of his lectures.

00:08:31.460 --> 00:08:34.130
They are fabulous,
and they're electric.

00:08:34.130 --> 00:08:36.559
And the reason is
sitting right here.

00:08:36.559 --> 00:08:39.980
This is a professor who asks
his students, asks all of us

00:08:39.980 --> 00:08:43.309
really, if you read his work,
to live as the sages did,

00:08:43.309 --> 00:08:46.970
to put philosophy into
practice, to see how it applies,

00:08:46.970 --> 00:08:50.300
to understand his contradictions
as you think about the choices

00:08:50.300 --> 00:08:53.270
and values of your
everyday life.

00:08:53.270 --> 00:08:55.520
His intellectual
work in that sense

00:08:55.520 --> 00:08:59.200
defines that aspect
of the forums mission.

00:08:59.200 --> 00:09:02.710
That is, to summon the
deep past, in this case

00:09:02.710 --> 00:09:05.470
the Chinese past,
the Asian past,

00:09:05.470 --> 00:09:07.900
into the service of
the present, using

00:09:07.900 --> 00:09:11.140
it to defamiliarize our
world, and to make new ways

00:09:11.140 --> 00:09:13.630
of being visible and viable.

00:09:13.630 --> 00:09:15.700
Please join me in
welcoming Michael,

00:09:15.700 --> 00:09:17.250
and welcome to the forum.

00:09:17.250 --> 00:09:19.100
[APPLAUSE]

00:09:19.600 --> 00:09:22.420
Thank you, thank you.

00:09:22.420 --> 00:09:24.850
Thank you so much, Ian, for
the much nice introduction.

00:09:24.850 --> 00:09:27.097
My deep thanks to you
and Professor Kelce

00:09:27.097 --> 00:09:28.180
for putting this together.

00:09:28.180 --> 00:09:30.050
This is such an
extraordinary forum.

00:09:30.050 --> 00:09:31.980
And it's a deep
honor for me today

00:09:31.980 --> 00:09:35.550
to introduce Professor Prasenjit
Duara, the first time this year

00:09:35.550 --> 00:09:38.730
in the session that we'll be
bringing in voices from Asia.

00:09:38.730 --> 00:09:41.700
And as we will see, with a voice
that will enable us to do so

00:09:41.700 --> 00:09:43.530
in truly extraordinary ways.

00:09:43.530 --> 00:09:46.710
Professor Duara has been
for years one of the leading

00:09:46.710 --> 00:09:48.630
figures, not simply
in helping us

00:09:48.630 --> 00:09:50.670
have a new
understanding of Asia,

00:09:50.670 --> 00:09:52.920
but much more
importantly allowing

00:09:52.920 --> 00:09:56.640
us to use the materials, the
indigenous concepts in Asia

00:09:56.640 --> 00:09:59.010
to rethink our most fundamental
assumptions, our most

00:09:59.010 --> 00:10:00.390
fundamental approaches.

00:10:00.390 --> 00:10:02.220
And we think, what
we used to think

00:10:02.220 --> 00:10:04.350
of as the big
questions, now posed

00:10:04.350 --> 00:10:06.120
in radically different ways.

00:10:06.120 --> 00:10:08.590
Prasenjit Duara first
broke onto the scene

00:10:08.590 --> 00:10:09.880
in-- with his first book.

00:10:09.880 --> 00:10:12.270
It was called Culture
Power in the State.

00:10:12.270 --> 00:10:16.260
It was an attempt to rethink
state formation in China

00:10:16.260 --> 00:10:18.480
in the first half
of the 20th century.

00:10:18.480 --> 00:10:21.120
But the way he does this
is not the way everyone

00:10:21.120 --> 00:10:22.840
else was doing it,
which is, of course,

00:10:22.840 --> 00:10:24.840
to look at how states operate.

00:10:24.840 --> 00:10:27.390
He actually begins
at the rural level,

00:10:27.390 --> 00:10:29.700
shows over the
course of 50 years

00:10:29.700 --> 00:10:32.870
the radical transformation
in the rural areas

00:10:32.870 --> 00:10:34.440
effected by the state.

00:10:34.440 --> 00:10:37.640
And thereby makes an argument
how we should understand

00:10:37.640 --> 00:10:40.110
new state formation in China.

00:10:40.110 --> 00:10:42.180
But he makes it very
clear, this should

00:10:42.180 --> 00:10:44.220
lead us to rethink
state formation in Asia

00:10:44.220 --> 00:10:47.910
in general, and state formation
throughout the entire world.

00:10:47.910 --> 00:10:50.340
In the subsequent decades
since the book was published,

00:10:50.340 --> 00:10:52.740
this has become one
of the key works

00:10:52.740 --> 00:10:56.370
in allowing us to rethink these
processes of state formation.

00:10:56.370 --> 00:10:59.340
Immediately, he moves
on to yet another work.

00:10:59.340 --> 00:11:02.700
This one is called Rescuing
History From the Nation.

00:11:02.700 --> 00:11:06.240
Arguing that yes, most
of our historiographies

00:11:06.240 --> 00:11:10.100
are dominated by accepted
notions of the nation state,

00:11:10.100 --> 00:11:11.850
and many people at the
time were saying we

00:11:11.850 --> 00:11:14.520
should work against this
and deconstruct our notions

00:11:14.520 --> 00:11:15.810
of the nation state.

00:11:15.810 --> 00:11:19.140
Prasenjit Duara was the leader
in saying absolutely true.

00:11:19.140 --> 00:11:21.610
But then what do we do next?

00:11:21.610 --> 00:11:24.180
And the book was an
attempt to actively rethink

00:11:24.180 --> 00:11:27.240
what history would mean if
we did not take the nation

00:11:27.240 --> 00:11:29.340
state as the central focus.

00:11:29.340 --> 00:11:31.830
Hereto, we have an
extraordinarily influential

00:11:31.830 --> 00:11:34.740
work that has really
helped us we conceptualize

00:11:34.740 --> 00:11:36.450
the practice of history.

00:11:36.450 --> 00:11:39.930
Following was his third book,
Sovereignty and Authenticity,

00:11:39.930 --> 00:11:42.540
an attempt to rethink our
notions of sovereignty,

00:11:42.540 --> 00:11:44.890
the nation state in Asia.

00:11:44.890 --> 00:11:47.500
But again, forcing it onto
an international level,

00:11:47.500 --> 00:11:49.440
and here again
forcing a fundamental

00:11:49.440 --> 00:11:51.540
rethinking of our assumptions.

00:11:51.540 --> 00:11:54.090
And most importantly,
his latest book,

00:11:54.090 --> 00:11:57.300
The Crisis of Global Modernity,
our discussion for tonight.

00:11:57.300 --> 00:12:00.120
A truly extraordinary
work, in which

00:12:00.120 --> 00:12:02.790
he forces a complete
rethinking not

00:12:02.790 --> 00:12:04.920
only of the rise of
modernity, which is not

00:12:04.920 --> 00:12:07.710
a minor topic in
itself, but even

00:12:07.710 --> 00:12:12.000
arguing that not just we need
to re-conceptualize modernity,

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:15.060
but how would we redo
history so we don't fall

00:12:15.060 --> 00:12:17.970
into the dangers of assuming
a modernity narrative even as

00:12:17.970 --> 00:12:19.380
were trying to deny it.

00:12:19.380 --> 00:12:21.570
He comes up with
a brilliant vision

00:12:21.570 --> 00:12:24.600
of history of
circulation, then rereads

00:12:24.600 --> 00:12:28.680
the entire so-called modern
period through such a history.

00:12:28.680 --> 00:12:31.980
As he goes, he rethinks
our fundamental assumptions

00:12:31.980 --> 00:12:34.080
about what secularized
states are,

00:12:34.080 --> 00:12:35.850
as they arose
during this period.

00:12:35.850 --> 00:12:39.030
