energy, which is the one
that is most important.

00:17:35.670 --> 00:17:38.970
That is to say, most
policymakers in much

00:17:38.970 --> 00:17:40.020
of the rest of the world.

00:17:42.840 --> 00:17:46.860
But also look to geoengineering
and market mechanisms

00:17:46.860 --> 00:17:48.690
to address these problems.

00:17:48.690 --> 00:17:50.820
Now, to begin with,
I'm not opposed.

00:17:50.820 --> 00:17:52.200
I'm certainly not sympathetic.

00:17:52.200 --> 00:17:54.720
I think we need
all that we can get

00:17:54.720 --> 00:17:59.080
to address the problems of
climate change that we have.

00:17:59.080 --> 00:18:03.510
But I think that geoengineering
and market solutions, market

00:18:03.510 --> 00:18:07.080
mechanisms, are really--

00:18:07.080 --> 00:18:10.950
have many, many side
problems, including

00:18:10.950 --> 00:18:15.770
the issues of delivery, of
governance, of many plans

00:18:15.770 --> 00:18:19.140
sort of sit-in the drawers
of scientists desks

00:18:19.140 --> 00:18:21.420
or in the files, I guess.

00:18:21.420 --> 00:18:24.000
And because of
problems of governance,

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:26.130
of cultural
understanding, of society,

00:18:26.130 --> 00:18:30.330
and most of all, of course,
of political ecology,

00:18:30.330 --> 00:18:33.090
and the politics of
these kinds of issues.

00:18:33.090 --> 00:18:36.720
And of course many also
geoengineering solutions

00:18:36.720 --> 00:18:39.360
can have all kinds of
disastrous side effects

00:18:39.360 --> 00:18:43.590
that require once again
civil society, and what

00:18:43.590 --> 00:18:48.430
is now known as citizen
science, to be able to address.

00:18:48.430 --> 00:18:51.550
So renewable energy
is, of course, great.

00:18:51.550 --> 00:18:53.730
But I don't think
that it can still

00:18:53.730 --> 00:18:56.580
alleviate our current rate
of accelerating climate

00:18:56.580 --> 00:18:59.760
change and rising ocean levels.

00:18:59.760 --> 00:19:03.540
I follow closely the economic--

00:19:03.540 --> 00:19:07.590
the ecological
economist Tim Jackson,

00:19:07.590 --> 00:19:09.810
who has a treadmill argument.

00:19:09.810 --> 00:19:15.810
He is the director of
the sustainable economy

00:19:15.810 --> 00:19:21.120
program in the UK, and is very
involved with the UN as well.

00:19:21.120 --> 00:19:27.990
And Tim Jackson argues from kind
of a semi-Marxist perspective

00:19:27.990 --> 00:19:32.910
that as long as we remain on
the treadmill of accelerating

00:19:32.910 --> 00:19:38.520
production, the reduction
of polluting energy inputs

00:19:38.520 --> 00:19:44.100
will simply increase its use for
higher production and profits.

00:19:44.100 --> 00:19:47.670
And at the same time,
increase the exploitation

00:19:47.670 --> 00:19:50.100
of other resources.

00:19:50.100 --> 00:19:54.180
I think one of the best
examples in recent times

00:19:54.180 --> 00:19:59.070
is the rarer quest, which
is really digging very

00:19:59.070 --> 00:20:02.460
deep in many parts of the
world, and also producing,

00:20:02.460 --> 00:20:03.960
of course, abysmal conditions.

00:20:03.960 --> 00:20:06.390
But it's necessary for
your and my cell phones

00:20:06.390 --> 00:20:09.150
and for everything
else that we're doing

00:20:09.150 --> 00:20:11.940
with contemporary technology.

00:20:11.940 --> 00:20:14.730
So ultimately, it
seems to me that we

00:20:14.730 --> 00:20:17.400
will need a kind of value
change in the world that

00:20:17.400 --> 00:20:20.910
can limit the mentality
of increasing GDP

00:20:20.910 --> 00:20:23.640
and consumption, that treadmill.

00:20:23.640 --> 00:20:25.350
At the same time,
of course, we need

00:20:25.350 --> 00:20:27.960
to address the
problem of poverty.

00:20:27.960 --> 00:20:30.660
Because after all, we cannot
stand up when the third world

00:20:30.660 --> 00:20:33.930
stands up and says OK,
you've had your goods.

00:20:33.930 --> 00:20:35.790
What about us?

00:20:35.790 --> 00:20:39.630
And so I think any notion
of environmental justice

00:20:39.630 --> 00:20:44.670
has to build that in a way that
the Paris climate conference

00:20:44.670 --> 00:20:48.540
did not necessarily address.

00:20:48.540 --> 00:20:51.000
Ecologists and people
like Tim Jackson

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:54.900
have tried valiantly to show
that the tools-- the problem

00:20:54.900 --> 00:21:00.240
of alleviation of poverty, and
the alleviation or at least

00:21:00.240 --> 00:21:04.500
addressing mitigation
of climate change

00:21:04.500 --> 00:21:09.090
are not necessarily
contradictory, particularly

00:21:09.090 --> 00:21:11.460
if we are committed--
if we do not

00:21:11.460 --> 00:21:16.110
remain committed to incessant
GDP growth as the only measure

00:21:16.110 --> 00:21:17.740
of prosperity.

00:21:17.740 --> 00:21:20.340
And they consider
many different-- how

00:21:20.340 --> 00:21:23.130
it is that our very
notion of prosperity

00:21:23.130 --> 00:21:26.790
has become reduced to
this kind of GDP growth.

00:21:26.790 --> 00:21:28.620
And it's only measured
in those kinds

00:21:28.620 --> 00:21:30.450
of terms, which
of course in turn

00:21:30.450 --> 00:21:38.410
involves increasing consumption
at a rapid rate and so on.

00:21:38.410 --> 00:21:41.520
And he talks about--

00:21:41.520 --> 00:21:45.420
he considers [INAUDIBLE],, who
is still at this university,

00:21:45.420 --> 00:21:45.920
right?

00:21:45.920 --> 00:21:46.280
Yes.

00:21:46.280 --> 00:21:46.779
OK, good.

00:21:46.779 --> 00:21:48.940
I could never figure
out where he is.

00:21:48.940 --> 00:21:51.810
That's a good point,
but [INAUDIBLE]

00:21:51.810 --> 00:21:53.610
capabilities ideas,
which I think

00:21:53.610 --> 00:21:55.230
are also very interesting.

00:21:55.230 --> 00:21:57.240
But of course, he has to--

00:21:57.240 --> 00:22:01.020
he has to, what should
I say, adapt them

00:22:01.020 --> 00:22:04.920
to the conditions
of what it means

00:22:04.920 --> 00:22:09.000
to have a fulfilling life
without necessarily going on

00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:11.640
by increasing capabilities.

00:22:11.640 --> 00:22:17.190
But not having sort of access to
the full resources of the world

00:22:17.190 --> 00:22:21.450
all the time, that is with
limited thresholds, right?

00:22:21.450 --> 00:22:25.320
And one of the things
that Tim Jackson argues

00:22:25.320 --> 00:22:30.440
is that as long as we can--

00:22:30.440 --> 00:22:33.720
he says that you can
have a satisfactory life

00:22:33.720 --> 00:22:38.820
to fulfill all kinds
of purposes with a,

00:22:38.820 --> 00:22:45.490
what he calculates, a $15,000
per capita income in the world.

00:22:45.490 --> 00:22:49.260
And if the world could
maintain it at that level,

00:22:49.260 --> 00:22:51.330
you could find
many different ways

00:22:51.330 --> 00:22:56.520
of achieving your
capacities and capabilities,

00:22:56.520 --> 00:22:58.740
and fulfilling your
desires for many things.

00:22:58.740 --> 00:23:02.010
It almost sounds like when
Marx talks about go fishing

00:23:02.010 --> 00:23:04.320
in the morning and hunting
in the evening and things

00:23:04.320 --> 00:23:07.560
like that in his communist
utopia, but with the Marx--

00:23:07.560 --> 00:23:11.370
but you may have to
do fishing, and not

00:23:11.370 --> 00:23:14.295
go on with your latest gadget.

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:20.580
Fly fishing, perhaps.

00:23:20.580 --> 00:23:23.280
So my work is really--

00:23:23.280 --> 00:23:26.970
now, the paper is designed to
probe this problem of value

00:23:26.970 --> 00:23:30.810
change and adjust to--

00:23:30.810 --> 00:23:33.210
I don't know anything
about Costa Rica

00:23:33.210 --> 00:23:34.950
except what I've given you.

00:23:34.950 --> 00:23:37.650
I was giving a class
lecture, and I was--

00:23:37.650 --> 00:23:39.840
I stumbled onto it.

00:23:39.840 --> 00:23:42.524
And it seems to me
the perfect example.

00:23:42.524 --> 00:23:44.190
And I'm sure that if
you will-- if there

00:23:44.190 --> 00:23:47.010
are Latin Americans you
will correct me, and show me

00:23:47.010 --> 00:23:49.840
how many problems there
are in Costa Rica.

00:23:49.840 --> 00:23:53.370
But they have a per
capita GDP of $12,000

00:23:53.370 --> 00:23:57.810
USD they have 5% of the
world's biodiversity,

00:23:57.810 --> 00:24:02.850
but the population is 0.06% of
the world's population, right?

00:24:02.850 --> 00:24:05.460
They have 25% of their
land is protected,

00:24:05.460 --> 00:24:07.640
as you can see in this map here.

00:24:07.640 --> 00:24:09.930
And 50% of the land is forested.

00:24:09.930 --> 00:24:12.450
It's not-- a lot of it
is new growth forest.

00:24:12.450 --> 00:24:14.100
It's not primeval
forests or something.

00:24:14.100 --> 00:24:16.320
But nonetheless, they have it.

00:24:16.320 --> 00:24:19.080
And the happiness planet--

00:24:19.080 --> 00:24:23.740
happy planet index
discovered it to be--

00:24:23.740 --> 00:24:27.780
rated it as the greenest and
happiest country for three

00:24:27.780 --> 00:24:29.680
years in a row in the world.

00:24:29.680 --> 00:24:32.910
It has displaced
Bhutan by far, and also

00:24:32.910 --> 00:24:36.135
many of the Scandinavian
countries in those indices.

00:24:38.750 --> 00:24:40.880
And it's not just
the happiness panel.

00:24:40.880 --> 00:24:43.620
Gallup poll also found the
Central American nation

00:24:43.620 --> 00:24:46.290
to have the highest level
of well-being in the world.

00:24:46.290 --> 00:24:51.000
So it's not-- it's not some
pie-in-the-sky goal that these

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:52.140
guys are talking about.

00:24:52.140 --> 00:24:55.800
I think a lot has to
be done, but there

00:24:55.800 --> 00:24:57.870
is-- it's in the
realm of possibility.

00:25:03.080 --> 00:25:05.050
So what is my argument?

00:25:05.050 --> 00:25:08.140
I argue that we begin to
see the glimmers of value

00:25:08.140 --> 00:25:12.010
change in a convergence
of historical trends

00:25:12.010 --> 00:25:16.060
of marginal, local communities
in Asia and elsewhere

00:25:16.060 --> 00:25:19.450
in the developing world seeking
to conserve their livelihood

00:25:19.450 --> 00:25:25.120
resources, and coming together
with modern groups committed

00:25:25.120 --> 00:25:28.630
to environmental
protection, right?

00:25:28.630 --> 00:25:31.810
This convergence, I argue, is
a kind of emergent phenomenon,

00:25:31.810 --> 00:25:36.850
in the fashionable sense of
the word emergent of Whitehead

00:25:36.850 --> 00:25:39.780
and others.

00:25:39.780 --> 00:25:42.160
But it is of course
a very weak force.

00:25:42.160 --> 00:25:44.530
But it is poised, I think,
on something very globally

00:25:44.530 --> 00:25:45.910
significant.

00:25:45.910 --> 00:25:50.470
They reflect a kind of
philosophical attitude that--

00:25:50.470 --> 00:25:53.110
and the possibilities
of a sustainable life

00:25:53.110 --> 00:25:57.910
in opposition to the
neo-liberal model that we have,

00:25:57.910 --> 00:26:00.490
that we have lived with now,
the neo-liberal capitalist,

00:26:00.490 --> 00:26:04.870
or even, what I would say,
the national modernization

00:26:04.870 --> 00:26:08.200
cosmology focused on
the conquest of nature,

00:26:08.200 --> 00:26:11.650
and to feed unending wealth.

00:26:11.650 --> 00:26:13.630
As I said, it's a weak position.

00:26:13.630 --> 00:26:16.360
There are lots of
weaknesses within

00:26:16.360 --> 00:26:18.970
this oppositional mosaic,
and we can talk about them.

00:26:18.970 --> 00:26:22.360
I'm not going to dwell on the
weaknesses so much this time.

00:26:22.360 --> 00:26:24.310
I'll mention them.

00:26:24.310 --> 00:26:31.150
But my goal is really to try and
see what this kind of position

00:26:31.150 --> 00:26:32.680
is, what kind of--

00:26:32.680 --> 00:26:37.660
is it possible to sort
of track it, to trace it,

00:26:37.660 --> 00:26:41.410
and to view it from world
historical patterns that are

00:26:41.410 --> 00:26:45.370
tied to ideas of transcendence.

00:26:45.370 --> 00:26:47.920
And my final
argument is that I do

00:26:47.920 --> 00:26:51.580
believe there is a concept,
a new concept of sick reality

00:26:51.580 --> 00:26:54.850
of nature that is
beginning to emerge,

00:26:54.850 --> 00:26:58.720
and that it has social
discursive as well

00:26:58.720 --> 00:27:01.660
as some legal
underpinnings globally.

00:27:01.660 --> 00:27:03.910
But you just have to
have the right optic

00:27:03.910 --> 00:27:05.170
to see how it's working.

00:27:08.770 --> 00:27:10.660
So I really want
to draw attention

00:27:10.660 --> 00:27:13.420
to this possibility
in the world.

00:27:13.420 --> 00:27:18.220
So I go into some
depth about some

00:27:18.220 --> 00:27:20.340
of the theoretical
concepts in the book

00:27:20.340 --> 00:27:22.420
and that have been
very important for me

00:27:22.420 --> 00:27:25.150
to understand this phenomenon.

00:27:25.150 --> 00:27:28.090
I use very much,
or a version of,

00:27:28.090 --> 00:27:30.940
it's not the orthodox
idea of transcendence

00:27:30.940 --> 00:27:33.940
that Axial Age
sociologists develop,

00:27:33.940 --> 00:27:37.600
including our teacher
Ben Schwartz was

00:27:37.600 --> 00:27:39.190
a very important part of this.

00:27:39.190 --> 00:27:42.280
In fact, I first heard
about it from him.

00:27:42.280 --> 00:27:46.150
But I have followed the
literature on transcendence.

00:27:46.150 --> 00:27:50.770
I see it not in the traditional
terms of a god or something

00:27:50.770 --> 00:27:53.990
like that, but really a
position of knowledge,

00:27:53.990 --> 00:27:57.040
what I call a meta epistemic
position of knowledge, I mean.

00:27:57.040 --> 00:28:00.860
It is something that people
have with material consequences,

00:28:00.860 --> 00:28:04.720
whether or not that transcendent
position is there or not

00:28:04.720 --> 00:28:07.210
is not significant to me.

00:28:07.210 --> 00:28:10.720
It works as if it is important
for the people who see it,

00:28:10.720 --> 00:28:12.210
right?

00:28:12.210 --> 00:28:15.220
And a lot of philosophers have
now been coming around to it.

00:28:15.220 --> 00:28:17.110
Charles Taylor has
become a big advocate.

00:28:17.110 --> 00:28:19.900
Even Jurgen Habermas,
who is of course

00:28:19.900 --> 00:28:23.050
your ultimate rationalist,
post-Marxist rationalist,

00:28:23.050 --> 00:28:24.950
has come around to
this point of view.

00:28:24.950 --> 00:28:28.120
And he, of course, is super
enthusiastic about it.

00:28:28.120 --> 00:28:31.570
He talks about this is the
transcendent position, which

00:28:31.570 --> 00:28:33.670
is a position from
outside the world,

00:28:33.670 --> 00:28:37.000
really allows you to get a
synoptic view of the world

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:39.610
as a whole, distinguishing
the flood of phenomena

00:28:39.610 --> 00:28:41.326
from underlying essence.

00:28:41.326 --> 00:28:42.700
And then he goes
on about how you

00:28:42.700 --> 00:28:46.200
get the difference between
health, and myth, and law.

00:28:46.200 --> 00:28:51.050
And it's just I think
he overdoes it, but--

00:28:51.050 --> 00:28:53.980
because it's not entirely that.

00:28:53.980 --> 00:28:57.310
But it is very much the
capacity for transcendence.

00:28:57.310 --> 00:28:59.170
If I had to define
it, is the capacity

00:28:59.170 --> 00:29:02.260
of abstraction from the
here and now, right?

00:29:02.260 --> 00:29:04.330
So it is the capacity.

00:29:04.330 --> 00:29:07.030
And it emerges, of
course, at the time

00:29:07.030 --> 00:29:10.330
when you begin to get
empires in the sixth century

00:29:10.330 --> 00:29:12.700
BC that spread across.

00:29:12.700 --> 00:29:14.350
And that's what the axial--

00:29:14.350 --> 00:29:17.110
axis-- I'm assuming most of
you are familiar with this,

00:29:17.110 --> 00:29:20.980
refers to the Axial Age
across the sixth century

00:29:20.980 --> 00:29:25.150
onwards, where you have
philosophers who posit

00:29:25.150 --> 00:29:28.840
this meta-epistemic locus.

00:29:28.840 --> 00:29:31.840
And it does refer to
the point at which there

00:29:31.840 --> 00:29:34.090
is the condition of
Universalism becomes

00:29:34.090 --> 00:29:37.060
possible, something
beyond the here and now.

00:29:37.060 --> 00:29:40.960
And it also generates a
reflexivity of the self

00:29:40.960 --> 00:29:44.020
and its position in relation
to this world, right?

00:29:44.020 --> 00:29:45.850
What is my status?

00:29:45.850 --> 00:29:47.920
What is the meaning
of my life in this?

00:29:47.920 --> 00:29:49.150
How do I relate to it?

00:29:49.150 --> 00:29:51.720
How do I relate to
the world around it?

00:29:51.720 --> 00:29:55.720
And how do I relate to power,
to material power in the here

00:29:55.720 --> 00:29:56.320
and now?

00:29:56.320 --> 00:29:59.860
How does this alternative
source of moral authority,

00:29:59.860 --> 00:30:04.120
which is beyond this world,
relate to power in the world?

00:30:04.120 --> 00:30:06.790
So it's a source of
ethics and ethical power.

00:30:06.790 --> 00:30:09.160
And this-- this
transcendent role

00:30:09.160 --> 00:30:10.990
has been completely
underestimated

00:30:10.990 --> 00:30:14.830
in historical studies.

00:30:14.830 --> 00:30:18.070
But if you look at it,
everywhere, it's everywhere.

00:30:18.070 --> 00:30:21.220
From the earliest periods,
you begin to get establishment

00:30:21.220 --> 00:30:24.640
institutions, whether it's the
church and the church-state

00:30:24.640 --> 00:30:28.780
relations, the Mandate
of Heaven, Bauman power .

00:30:28.780 --> 00:30:30.760
These are, of course,
become establishment.

00:30:30.760 --> 00:30:32.410
I mean, the whole
idea is that once you

00:30:32.410 --> 00:30:34.930
have a hold on
transcendent power,

00:30:34.930 --> 00:30:37.420
then political power wants
to grab that as well, right?

00:30:37.420 --> 00:30:38.680
As always.

00:30:38.680 --> 00:30:40.720
But then you also have
oppositional movements

00:30:40.720 --> 00:30:42.870
that are based on
this, whether this is--

00:30:42.870 --> 00:30:45.040
the most important is
the Protestant movement

00:30:45.040 --> 00:30:46.070
that we know about.

00:30:46.070 --> 00:30:48.260
But they are all
through history,

00:30:48.260 --> 00:30:51.340
whether it's Franciscans, Sufis,
Buddhists against Brahmans,

00:30:51.340 --> 00:30:53.470
Buddhist [INAUDIBLE],,
the [INAUDIBLE] movement,

00:30:53.470 --> 00:30:57.730
the Confucian movement, the
Taoists, Thoreau, Gandhi,

00:30:57.730 --> 00:30:58.960
Martin Luther King.

00:30:58.960 --> 00:31:02.530
I mean, all these people really
work on this alternative source

00:31:02.530 --> 00:31:05.320
of moral authority, right?

00:31:05.320 --> 00:31:07.200
And the problem
with the Axial Age

00:31:07.200 --> 00:31:09.670
is that they thought it
happened just once, right?

00:31:09.670 --> 00:31:11.390
But it's a recurrent phenomenon.

00:31:11.390 --> 00:31:14.290
And in that sense, it
becomes a historical process.

00:31:14.290 --> 00:31:17.230
It's very much part
of historical process.

00:31:17.230 --> 00:31:21.400
And it's very important for
renewal, social renewal.

00:31:21.400 --> 00:31:24.790
So, and part of the
argument in the book

00:31:24.790 --> 00:31:26.260
is that there is
a big difference

00:31:26.260 --> 00:31:29.410
between transcendence in
the Abrahamic societies

00:31:29.410 --> 00:31:31.160
and in the non
Abrahamic societies.

00:31:31.160 --> 00:31:34.150
And the book goes on
to discuss a great deal

00:31:34.150 --> 00:31:35.000
of this difference.

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:37.750
But I do want to say that
what Max Weber called

00:31:37.750 --> 00:31:40.270
the intellectual
religions of the east

00:31:40.270 --> 00:31:44.570
did not have an omnipotent god
in that transcendent position,

00:31:44.570 --> 00:31:45.680
right?

00:31:45.680 --> 00:31:48.340
But more rational
techniques of cultivation,

00:31:48.340 --> 00:31:50.430
whether these are
ethical self cultivation

00:31:50.430 --> 00:31:53.080
is a big term in
Neo-Confucianism,

00:31:53.080 --> 00:31:57.370
yogic, meditative in approaching
transcendent authority, rather

00:31:57.370 --> 00:31:59.860
than pure faith or
just secularization.

00:31:59.860 --> 00:32:02.080
So there is a measure
of rationality

00:32:02.080 --> 00:32:04.750
that we will, of
course, always recognize

00:32:04.750 --> 00:32:07.270
that underlaid the
sacred authority that

00:32:07.270 --> 00:32:09.370
was involved in that.

00:32:09.370 --> 00:32:11.710
So all the major
problems of the world

00:32:11.710 --> 00:32:14.080
manifest themselves, the
environmental problems

00:32:14.080 --> 00:32:17.140
that we have today,
locally and can best

00:32:17.140 --> 00:32:21.670
be addressed perhaps locally
without a universal vision

00:32:21.670 --> 00:32:24.250
that the transcendent
position gives us,

00:32:24.250 --> 00:32:25.990
that locus can give us.

00:32:25.990 --> 00:32:29.830
It becomes a problem of kicking
the can down the road, right?

00:32:29.830 --> 00:32:31.480
It becomes nimby.

00:32:31.480 --> 00:32:33.700
We don't want this
chemical factory here,

00:32:33.700 --> 00:32:35.020
take it somewhere else.

00:32:35.020 --> 00:32:36.020
That doesn't address it.

00:32:36.020 --> 00:32:38.140
And this is happening
all over the world.

00:32:38.140 --> 00:32:41.380
Today, Thailand is produce--

00:32:41.380 --> 00:32:44.680
it is constructing its
most polluting industries

00:32:44.680 --> 00:32:49.537
in the Burmese strip,
which adjoins it.

00:32:49.537 --> 00:32:52.120
That's where it does it, because
there is no movement in Burma

00:32:52.120 --> 00:32:54.040
against it in that space.

00:32:54.040 --> 00:32:57.301
There is on the Myitsone Dam,
and the Irrawaddy river and so

00:32:57.301 --> 00:32:57.800
on.

00:32:57.800 --> 00:32:59.560
There's huge civil
society movement,

00:32:59.560 --> 00:33:00.640
but not in that space.

00:33:00.640 --> 00:33:02.980
And there's nobody
there to complain.

00:33:02.980 --> 00:33:05.260
So you-- so what I
argue in the book

00:33:05.260 --> 00:33:08.500
is a position of for
dialogical transcendence,

00:33:08.500 --> 00:33:10.640
where you can have
this back and forth,

00:33:10.640 --> 00:33:12.280
which becomes very
difficult, much

00:33:12.280 --> 00:33:14.710
more difficult in the
Abrahamic traditions, which

00:33:14.710 --> 00:33:18.730
has a much broader sense
of the transcendent.

00:33:18.730 --> 00:33:22.690
So, one of the
principal problems

00:33:22.690 --> 00:33:25.870
in addressing the universal
or planetary dimensions

00:33:25.870 --> 00:33:27.400
is of course
nationalism, something

00:33:27.400 --> 00:33:31.536
I've railed about for
about 30 years now.

00:33:31.536 --> 00:33:34.270
Though I've become much
more sensible towards it,

00:33:34.270 --> 00:33:37.900
I think, the problem of
national sovereignty,

00:33:37.900 --> 00:33:42.460
which prevents collaborative
solving of common problems.

00:33:42.460 --> 00:33:45.310
And I'll just show you one
picture of the Himalayan

00:33:45.310 --> 00:33:46.630
rivers.

00:33:46.630 --> 00:33:51.460
And it locks national leaders
into this whole competitive GDP

00:33:51.460 --> 00:33:54.670
and resource
control game, right?

00:33:54.670 --> 00:33:56.650
So one of the things--
the other thing

00:33:56.650 --> 00:33:58.810
that I try to do in
this book is also

00:33:58.810 --> 00:34:03.340
talk about how the idea
of national sovereignty

00:34:03.340 --> 00:34:06.160
is so closely tied
up with the idea

00:34:06.160 --> 00:34:09.580
of modern national history, of
modern history, which of course

00:34:09.580 --> 00:34:12.340
began as national histories.

00:34:12.340 --> 00:34:17.889
And that it has the
role, by talking about,

00:34:17.889 --> 00:34:24.159
by seeing history as linear
and tunneled from origins

00:34:24.159 --> 00:34:29.530
to destiny, it becomes a means
of claiming sovereignty, right?

00:34:29.530 --> 00:34:32.020
This is our people, our land,
our tradition, our culture,

00:34:32.020 --> 00:34:33.380
you get out.

00:34:33.380 --> 00:34:35.050
And besides, you
cannot interfere.

00:34:37.610 --> 00:34:41.690
So, it prioritizes
national interest way

00:34:41.690 --> 00:34:44.690
above the planetary
interests, right?

00:34:44.690 --> 00:34:46.760
In a way, the
universal transcendence

00:34:46.760 --> 00:34:49.250
of pre-national
religions has been

00:34:49.250 --> 00:34:52.040
blocked at the
nation as the highest

00:34:52.040 --> 00:34:54.980
level of transcendent--
transcendence,

00:34:54.980 --> 00:34:58.580
and mobilize for Tribalist
and capitalist competition.

00:34:58.580 --> 00:35:01.700
This is my general take
on nationalism in general.

00:35:01.700 --> 00:35:05.450
So what I try to do, as
you pointed out Michael,

00:35:05.450 --> 00:35:12.320
is that I tried to
substitute not circulation,

00:35:12.320 --> 00:35:16.460
but circulatory histories
for the linear tunnel

00:35:16.460 --> 00:35:18.260
histories of nations
and civilizations

00:35:18.260 --> 00:35:21.920
with the idea of
circulatory histories.

00:35:21.920 --> 00:35:23.000
And now, I'm trying to--

00:35:23.000 --> 00:35:24.750
I'm developing a paper on it.

00:35:24.750 --> 00:35:25.850
And one of the--

00:35:25.850 --> 00:35:31.130
one of the common sort of
ways in which I thought

00:35:31.130 --> 00:35:34.370
could be very usable was the
Deleuze and Guattari idea

00:35:34.370 --> 00:35:37.250
of rhizomatiks,
right, which were

00:35:37.250 --> 00:35:39.530
the same thing can appear
in different places

00:35:39.530 --> 00:35:41.330
simultaneously.

00:35:41.330 --> 00:35:43.530
But I'm now much more
persuaded, although I

00:35:43.530 --> 00:35:46.070
have to study much more
physics for that, to talk

00:35:46.070 --> 00:35:47.930
about in terms of
currents, ocean

00:35:47.930 --> 00:35:54.350
currents, and the whole sort
of ocean physics in a way,

00:35:54.350 --> 00:35:56.300
and how that also redistributes.

00:35:56.300 --> 00:35:59.060
And it ties back, of course,
to the natural sphere

00:35:59.060 --> 00:36:00.630
in very interesting
kinds of ways.

00:36:00.630 --> 00:36:03.280
So does the rhizome, but--

00:36:03.280 --> 00:36:05.260
but I'm still working on that.

00:36:05.260 --> 00:36:06.920
So maybe in a year.

00:36:11.890 --> 00:36:13.600
So, what is circulatory history?

00:36:13.600 --> 00:36:17.190
Events have effects that
disperse over space and time,

00:36:17.190 --> 00:36:18.010
right?

00:36:18.010 --> 00:36:22.530
A major wall can have
distant effects on prices,

00:36:22.530 --> 00:36:29.230
or political alliances in third,
fourth 20,000 other places.

00:36:29.230 --> 00:36:31.930
And I'll just give a
personal narrative.

00:36:31.930 --> 00:36:36.080
Not a personal, a personal
historical narrative,

00:36:36.080 --> 00:36:38.870
which is the case of the Ahomes.

00:36:38.870 --> 00:36:41.650
The Ahomes-- I come
from a part of India

00:36:41.650 --> 00:36:44.840
called Assam in northeast India.

00:36:44.840 --> 00:36:46.600
Here, you can see that.

00:36:46.600 --> 00:36:48.450
Where is the pointer?

00:36:48.450 --> 00:36:49.600
Is the pointer working?

00:36:49.600 --> 00:36:51.881
Do I point here?

00:36:51.881 --> 00:36:53.050
Yeah, there it is.

00:36:53.050 --> 00:36:57.670
This is Assam, where you have
the Brahmaputra River out here,

00:36:57.670 --> 00:36:58.750
right?

00:36:58.750 --> 00:37:03.260
Now, and this is, you can
see, it is Yunnan, right?

00:37:03.260 --> 00:37:06.760
Just around here, Yunnan.

00:37:06.760 --> 00:37:10.450
The Ahomes came to
the Brahmaputra region

00:37:10.450 --> 00:37:12.700
in the 13th century.

00:37:12.700 --> 00:37:16.900
They were part of the Dali
kingdom, or the Delhi kingdom,

00:37:16.900 --> 00:37:19.570
until the 14th century, which
was an independent Buddhist

00:37:19.570 --> 00:37:24.850
kingdom not controlled
by the Chinese empires.

00:37:24.850 --> 00:37:29.200
Until the Mongols come, and
then the Mongols overrun it,

00:37:29.200 --> 00:37:31.150
and the Thais are gone.

00:37:31.150 --> 00:37:35.390
It's not exactly true, but
it's pretty close to the truth.

00:37:35.390 --> 00:37:39.640
Go on to create Thailand,
what is now the--

00:37:39.640 --> 00:37:43.120
the Thais of Thailand, where
is one of the very important

00:37:43.120 --> 00:37:45.340
vessels groups comes--

00:37:45.340 --> 00:37:48.580
come over, go to the west,
to the Brahmaputra River,

00:37:48.580 --> 00:37:49.900
called the Ahomes.

00:37:49.900 --> 00:37:54.070
And manage-- they have very
good river technologies.

00:37:54.070 --> 00:37:55.720
And they keep out the Mongols.

00:37:55.720 --> 00:37:56.530
They keep out.

00:37:56.530 --> 00:37:58.460
And it's not until
the 19th century,

00:37:58.460 --> 00:38:00.910
when the British conquered
them, that you have it.

00:38:00.910 --> 00:38:02.410
So what they also import--

00:38:02.410 --> 00:38:03.632
they Hinduize after a while.

00:38:03.632 --> 00:38:06.090
They [INAUDIBLE],, and they
import people from north India.

00:38:06.090 --> 00:38:09.950
And people of my class
background from Assam

00:38:09.950 --> 00:38:12.980
will say oh yes, we are
from those families,

00:38:12.980 --> 00:38:14.560
whether or not we
are from there.

00:38:14.560 --> 00:38:17.110
Nonetheless, it is
the Mongol invasion

00:38:17.110 --> 00:38:20.200
that made us who we are
there right now, right?

00:38:20.200 --> 00:38:23.740
So talk about the effects
of circulatory histories.

00:38:26.420 --> 00:38:30.170
Now of course, and I always
take the example of it's

00:38:30.170 --> 00:38:32.150
also narratives which change.

00:38:32.150 --> 00:38:35.480
With the dispersal of the event,
and the effects of the events,

00:38:35.480 --> 00:38:37.730
the narratives also change.

00:38:37.730 --> 00:38:45.350
So at the time of the 1940s,
you had Japanese imperialism

00:38:45.350 --> 00:38:47.420
celebrating its great victories.

00:38:47.420 --> 00:38:49.490
With today, it's
turned against it

00:38:49.490 --> 00:38:51.590
very much by those
very people, places

00:38:51.590 --> 00:38:54.260
where it is, where there's
Taiwanese Aboriginals,

00:38:54.260 --> 00:38:58.010
or Koreans, or
Chinese, and so on.

00:38:58.010 --> 00:39:02.180
And there may even come a time
when, well, they resisted it

00:39:02.180 --> 00:39:04.610
so far, when Japanese
schoolchildren are reading

00:39:04.610 --> 00:39:07.160
textbooks about their
imperial history that

00:39:07.160 --> 00:39:12.030
has a very different view from
what it was at a certain time.

00:39:12.030 --> 00:39:16.430
So there is a certain
sort of looping back

00:39:16.430 --> 00:39:18.380
to events and their
concatenations

00:39:18.380 --> 00:39:20.730
with different
meanings and endings.

00:39:20.730 --> 00:39:24.210
So this is the way in which
history really circulates,

00:39:24.210 --> 00:39:26.120
is circulatory, both in--

00:39:26.120 --> 00:39:28.640
I also give this other
example of Marxism

00:39:28.640 --> 00:39:32.030
coming into China from several
different sources, right?

00:39:32.030 --> 00:39:36.420
Japan, Russia,
France, and so on.

00:39:36.420 --> 00:39:38.000
But it comes in.

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:40.460
Of course, the local
force transforms it,

00:39:40.460 --> 00:39:42.640
becomes a peasant
revolution, right?

00:39:42.640 --> 00:39:44.270
Maoism taught.

00:39:44.270 --> 00:39:46.310
But then-- and
that goes out then,

00:39:46.310 --> 00:39:48.120
cycles out to the
rest of the world.

00:39:48.120 --> 00:39:49.550
But what does it become now?

00:39:49.550 --> 00:39:52.310
Essentially, if you look
at what Maoism is today,

00:39:52.310 --> 00:39:53.729
it is a Tribalist movement.

00:39:53.729 --> 00:39:55.520
You have it among
[INAUDIBLE],, you have it

00:39:55.520 --> 00:40:00.590
among Central Asians, you have
it among central India in Nepal

00:40:00.590 --> 00:40:01.880
and these kinds of places.

00:40:01.880 --> 00:40:04.370
They're essentially
Tribalist movements.

00:40:04.370 --> 00:40:07.610
And so you have these
kinds of transformations,

00:40:07.610 --> 00:40:10.171
but the reference is still back
to a certain type of Marxism,

00:40:10.171 --> 00:40:10.670
right?

00:40:10.670 --> 00:40:13.130
That's going around
and shaping societies

00:40:13.130 --> 00:40:14.520
and reshaping society.

00:40:14.520 --> 00:40:17.060
So that's the kind of
thing I want to talk about.

00:40:17.060 --> 00:40:21.440
The important point here is that
history is a shared planetary

00:40:21.440 --> 00:40:22.610
heritage.

00:40:22.610 --> 00:40:25.580
We need to realize transcendence
at a planetary level

00:40:25.580 --> 00:40:28.460
to match the global
nature of human history,

00:40:28.460 --> 00:40:31.220
and the problems humans
have created, right?

00:40:31.220 --> 00:40:39.380
So it's really going to be very
difficult to validly depict

00:40:39.380 --> 00:40:42.650
national histories as the basis
of the kind of sovereignty

00:40:42.650 --> 00:40:47.540
that opposes all
kinds of interventions

00:40:47.540 --> 00:40:49.580
that are necessary.

00:40:49.580 --> 00:40:53.000
So here-- I mean, this
has been well studied.

00:40:53.000 --> 00:40:55.200
The Himalayan
rivers, as you know,

00:40:55.200 --> 00:41:01.685
have produced life for
over a billion people,

00:41:01.685 --> 00:41:05.780
billion and a half, and
many, many species around

00:41:05.780 --> 00:41:08.210
in the circa Himalayan region.

00:41:08.210 --> 00:41:11.390
And what is happening with
glacial melting, river

00:41:11.390 --> 00:41:13.970
diversions, which is
happening in China, and now

00:41:13.970 --> 00:41:15.590
also in India.

00:41:15.590 --> 00:41:20.780
And a dam building, most of
all, are endangering the sources

00:41:20.780 --> 00:41:23.000
of livelihoods of these people.

00:41:23.000 --> 00:41:25.160
And intergovernmental
cooperation

00:41:25.160 --> 00:41:27.240
is absolutely essential.

00:41:27.240 --> 00:41:29.330
But you find that there
are three countries

00:41:29.330 --> 00:41:32.240
in the world in
particular who refuse

00:41:32.240 --> 00:41:36.620
to share information and
cooperate internationally

00:41:36.620 --> 00:41:38.300
on river knowledge.

00:41:38.300 --> 00:41:42.890
And how much sedimentation
is taking place, how much.

00:41:42.890 --> 00:41:46.730
And they are, as you
would guess, one is China,

00:41:46.730 --> 00:41:50.060
one is Turkey, and
the third is Rwanda.

00:41:50.060 --> 00:41:52.560
And you know what they
all have in common?

00:41:52.560 --> 00:41:55.720
Any guesses?

00:41:55.720 --> 00:41:58.870
Rivers originate
in those countries.

00:41:58.870 --> 00:42:01.630
I was standing there giving
this talk in a Tibetan student

00:42:01.630 --> 00:42:06.380
government, I said, oh,
that would be Tibet.

00:42:06.380 --> 00:42:11.700
And so there was, yes, I guess
if you can make that claim.

00:42:11.700 --> 00:42:13.750
So this is a huge
problem, right?

00:42:13.750 --> 00:42:16.480
That you cannot find out.

00:42:16.480 --> 00:42:18.670
It's not-- it's
not easy to have.

00:42:18.670 --> 00:42:22.150
And the Mekong Commission,
which is among the most active,

00:42:22.150 --> 00:42:24.220
and there's a lot of
work on Mekong calling

00:42:24.220 --> 00:42:27.070
about social act, civil
society activists,

00:42:27.070 --> 00:42:30.950
and political activists, is
been one of the most successful.

00:42:30.950 --> 00:42:35.810
But still way, way
below what should be--

00:42:35.810 --> 00:42:38.910
what should be happening there.

00:42:38.910 --> 00:42:41.750
So is it possible to
elevate sustainability

00:42:41.750 --> 00:42:44.540
to a transcendent level, right?

00:42:44.540 --> 00:42:47.510
It seems to me most
people will say, well,

00:42:47.510 --> 00:42:50.710
it's corporations and
capitalism and so on.

00:42:50.710 --> 00:42:54.030
Well, certainly that
is definitely an issue.

00:42:54.030 --> 00:42:57.470
But I think the
more proximate issue

00:42:57.470 --> 00:42:59.780
is the problem of
national leaders

00:42:59.780 --> 00:43:03.410
and how they're so tied
in to the ideologies

00:43:03.410 --> 00:43:06.000
of national interests.

00:43:06.000 --> 00:43:08.120
For example, you
had the proposal

00:43:08.120 --> 00:43:14.480
of Mutsuyoshi Nishimura, who
was the first in the Kyoto

00:43:14.480 --> 00:43:18.290
Protocol, he was the chief
climate negotiator for Japan.

00:43:18.290 --> 00:43:24.620
And he had a very simple,
a very elegant proposal.

00:43:24.620 --> 00:43:27.650
He said the government
should collectively

00:43:27.650 --> 00:43:34.220
own a capped carbon budget of
$660 billion gigatons of CO2

00:43:34.220 --> 00:43:38.580
in total emissions
between 2010 and 2050.

00:43:38.580 --> 00:43:41.570
And then he had this
idea that these credits

00:43:41.570 --> 00:43:45.610
will be auctioned off on
a polluter pay principle.

00:43:45.610 --> 00:43:49.940
And that those
payments will then

00:43:49.940 --> 00:43:53.870
seek to recover the
damages that were caused.

00:43:53.870 --> 00:43:57.410
And he had all kinds of
provisions for handicapped--

00:43:57.410 --> 00:44:01.490
for handicapped provisions for
developing societies and so on.

00:44:01.490 --> 00:44:04.100
And it was something
that certainly the NGOs

00:44:04.100 --> 00:44:05.990
who had been among
the main forces

00:44:05.990 --> 00:44:09.500
behind all these climate
change talks, had agreed on.

00:44:09.500 --> 00:44:11.270
And they had the
principle agreement

00:44:11.270 --> 00:44:12.450
on this kind of thing.

00:44:12.450 --> 00:44:14.630
But it was always the
national governments

00:44:14.630 --> 00:44:18.911
that would claim national
mitigation circumstances

00:44:18.911 --> 00:44:19.410
and so on.

00:44:19.410 --> 00:44:22.010
And for a long time, it
was China and the US.

00:44:22.010 --> 00:44:24.447
The US saying you all, you're
polluting totally much more.

00:44:24.447 --> 00:44:26.030
And then China was
saying well, you've

00:44:26.030 --> 00:44:29.780
done it historically per
capita so much more, and so on.

00:44:29.780 --> 00:44:35.960
Then finally we get to
some kind of first step

00:44:35.960 --> 00:44:40.760
with the Paris 2015 UN
Climate Change Conference,

00:44:40.760 --> 00:44:43.190
what is known as COP 21.

00:44:43.190 --> 00:44:45.750
And that was a huge
moment of celebration,

00:44:45.750 --> 00:44:47.330
although it was just
the first stage.

00:44:47.330 --> 00:44:49.550
Because it was all
voluntary, and it and it

00:44:49.550 --> 00:44:53.630
didn't have anything to
do with your capacities

00:44:53.630 --> 00:44:55.170
to implement any of that.

00:44:55.170 --> 00:44:56.780
And then we come
to a stage now when

00:44:56.780 --> 00:44:58.880
that's off the table
with the US, right?

00:44:58.880 --> 00:45:01.890
So we'll have to
see now what's--

00:45:01.890 --> 00:45:06.260
so it's always many steps
backwards at every point.

00:45:06.260 --> 00:45:09.500
So although, as I said,
government and inter-government

00:45:09.500 --> 00:45:12.410
agencies are officially
behind this effort,

00:45:12.410 --> 00:45:14.120
it is really global
civil society

00:45:14.120 --> 00:45:17.460
that is the main pressure
group behind them,

00:45:17.460 --> 00:45:21.170
NGOs, quasi-government
agencies, like IBCC

00:45:21.170 --> 00:45:24.260
and things like that,
private-public initiatives.

00:45:24.260 --> 00:45:26.300
All of these have
been very important

00:45:26.300 --> 00:45:29.480
in this whole
movement in the world.

00:45:29.480 --> 00:45:31.880
And not least among these
is the transformation

00:45:31.880 --> 00:45:35.480
of religious societies
in the world.

00:45:35.480 --> 00:45:38.760
Now, of course, the pope
has gotten very big into it.

00:45:38.760 --> 00:45:43.370
But until recently, it was many
Asian societies which had--

00:45:43.370 --> 00:45:45.410
Asian religious
group which embed

00:45:45.410 --> 00:45:50.360
dialogical but authoritative
realm for self formation

00:45:50.360 --> 00:45:53.030
and values renewal, right?

00:45:53.030 --> 00:45:57.800
So what I want to discuss is the
tendency towards the converging

00:45:57.800 --> 00:46:02.750
goals for both religious and
non-religious social groups,

00:46:02.750 --> 00:46:06.230
civil societies, is
linked by this idea

00:46:06.230 --> 00:46:11.630
of ecological spirituality,
which Buddha talked about.

00:46:11.630 --> 00:46:14.960
First, let me talk a little
bit about cultural circulations

00:46:14.960 --> 00:46:16.580
in the Anthropocene.

00:46:16.580 --> 00:46:19.520
So it's part of the circulatory
history moment, right?

00:46:19.520 --> 00:46:21.440
One of the examples
I give in my book

00:46:21.440 --> 00:46:23.990
that people seem to
enjoy much is the idea

00:46:23.990 --> 00:46:26.960
of Ram Mohan Roy, who
is often considered

00:46:26.960 --> 00:46:28.340
the father of modern India.

00:46:28.340 --> 00:46:32.570
And in 1831 he was in Bristol.

00:46:32.570 --> 00:46:33.410
He was a Unitarian.

00:46:33.410 --> 00:46:36.770
He was a-- he was a
Vendantist, but he

00:46:36.770 --> 00:46:41.950
saw an equation between the
Vendanta and Unitarianism.

00:46:41.950 --> 00:46:45.560
And he was in Bristol.

00:46:45.560 --> 00:46:49.470
And I found this letter
circulating in Peabody,

00:46:49.470 --> 00:46:51.020
in the Peabody--

00:46:51.020 --> 00:46:55.340
in the Salem archive that
has this little fragment

00:46:55.340 --> 00:46:59.120
that Ram Mohan Roy
will come in to Salem.

00:46:59.120 --> 00:47:03.920
And so we are circulating
this lock of hair of his,

00:47:03.920 --> 00:47:06.770
in order to sort of celebrate
his saintliness and things

00:47:06.770 --> 00:47:07.980
like that.

00:47:07.980 --> 00:47:12.710
And he couldn't come, because
he dies just then in 1831.

00:47:12.710 --> 00:47:15.980
And so but then
apparently that opened up

00:47:15.980 --> 00:47:19.280
a whole archive, which showed
how Thoreau and Emerson had

00:47:19.280 --> 00:47:21.110
read some of his
translations and well,

00:47:21.110 --> 00:47:24.350
other translations also, but
had read some of his stuff

00:47:24.350 --> 00:47:26.150
and were preparing
to start over.

00:47:26.150 --> 00:47:27.740
And this led very
much to the kind

00:47:27.740 --> 00:47:31.940
of Peruvian transcendentalism,
right, which in turn--

00:47:31.940 --> 00:47:34.170
and civil disobedience,
which, in turn,

00:47:34.170 --> 00:47:36.200
influences someone like Gandhi.

00:47:36.200 --> 00:47:38.970
Although Gandhi doesn't fully
admit it, but through Tolstoy

00:47:38.970 --> 00:47:41.140
it influences Gandhi.

00:47:41.140 --> 00:47:43.090
And Gandhi then, of
course, influences

00:47:43.090 --> 00:47:44.410
Martin Luther King, right?

00:47:44.410 --> 00:47:49.370
So you get the sort of looping
back and forth the whole time,

00:47:49.370 --> 00:47:53.050
which is part of this cultural
circulations, right, of what we

00:47:53.050 --> 00:47:56.260
can call spirituality, right?

00:47:56.260 --> 00:47:57.940
So they are-- they
have typically

00:47:57.940 --> 00:48:00.370
been thought of as
counter-cultural movements

00:48:00.370 --> 00:48:04.240
among hippies, or urban groups,
or rural reconstructions

00:48:04.240 --> 00:48:05.170
in East Asia.

00:48:05.170 --> 00:48:06.690
I think they're very important.

00:48:06.690 --> 00:48:08.950
And in the Transpacific,
but I think

00:48:08.950 --> 00:48:11.110
they're developing
a new relevance

00:48:11.110 --> 00:48:14.740
as their causes become
tied to the most

00:48:14.740 --> 00:48:18.410
marginal groups in
Asian societies,

00:48:18.410 --> 00:48:20.500
and I would say in
Latin American societies

00:48:20.500 --> 00:48:25.100
and African societies to
a lesser extent as well.

00:48:25.100 --> 00:48:27.700
So on the one hand, you have
American spiritualist movements

00:48:27.700 --> 00:48:30.610
that embrace a
holistic view of nature

00:48:30.610 --> 00:48:34.180
from Thoreau, to deep
ecologists, to World Wildlife,

00:48:34.180 --> 00:48:36.910
to all of these
kinds of agencies.

00:48:36.910 --> 00:48:40.900
Both, I would say, on the
extreme wilderness Ang

00:48:40.900 --> 00:48:44.350
side, but also the corporatist
types like Conservation

00:48:44.350 --> 00:48:46.499
International and so on,
who I think also have

00:48:46.499 --> 00:48:47.665
some very interesting ideas.

00:48:51.420 --> 00:48:55.120
But they're forging
linkages with groups

00:48:55.120 --> 00:48:57.400
that are developing
around Gandhian ideas,

00:48:57.400 --> 00:49:01.180
around Buddhist forests
monks, among Daoist temples,

00:49:01.180 --> 00:49:03.280
and others as well.

00:49:03.280 --> 00:49:06.234
So at first glance, this
seems like little driblets

00:49:06.234 --> 00:49:07.150
that are going around.

00:49:07.150 --> 00:49:08.566
But I think one
of the things that

00:49:08.566 --> 00:49:11.800
is really transforming them
is this hyper-connectedness

00:49:11.800 --> 00:49:12.940
of our age.

00:49:12.940 --> 00:49:14.830
And I'll talk a
little bit about how

00:49:14.830 --> 00:49:16.840
this kind of the
new civil society

00:49:16.840 --> 00:49:19.300
that-- the new media
civil society, which

00:49:19.300 --> 00:49:21.370
also has such
destructive effects,

00:49:21.370 --> 00:49:25.800
can also create new types
of allegiances and alliances

00:49:25.800 --> 00:49:29.500
that give it a certain
flexibility and resilience,

00:49:29.500 --> 00:49:30.060
I think.

00:49:30.060 --> 00:49:35.830
You can just look at Hong Kong,
the way it's been resilient.

00:49:35.830 --> 00:49:39.070
What they do is these different
types of movements that

00:49:39.070 --> 00:49:41.350
are converging, I
think they converge

00:49:41.350 --> 00:49:45.800
upon a non-binary philosophical
attitude with consequences

00:49:45.800 --> 00:49:49.330
not only for lifestyle changes,
but for the ecological future

00:49:49.330 --> 00:49:52.320
of the planet.

00:49:52.320 --> 00:49:54.900
As I keep saying, it
is a very weak force,

00:49:54.900 --> 00:49:56.790
but a very resilient
form of politics

00:49:56.790 --> 00:49:59.970
that networks across the
global space of the new media

00:49:59.970 --> 00:50:01.530
to achieve some of its goals.

00:50:01.530 --> 00:50:04.990
I'll give you some
examples of that.

00:50:04.990 --> 00:50:07.980
First, we-- just a little
explanation on the term

00:50:07.980 --> 00:50:09.090
spirituality.

00:50:09.090 --> 00:50:12.960
The way I define spirituality,
also taken in collaboration

00:50:12.960 --> 00:50:15.000
with Peter van der
Veer and others,

00:50:15.000 --> 00:50:21.300
is that really it is a residual
realm for the transcendent that

00:50:21.300 --> 00:50:24.210
comes, that emerges
with the global trend

00:50:24.210 --> 00:50:27.780
towards secularization,
privatization of religion,

00:50:27.780 --> 00:50:30.960
the destructuralization, and
particularly the laicization,

00:50:30.960 --> 00:50:33.677
especially in Europe
that happens here,

00:50:33.677 --> 00:50:35.760
which is I think at the
root of the green movement

00:50:35.760 --> 00:50:37.530
and so on as well.

00:50:37.530 --> 00:50:40.080
Modern spirituality
as such is a new step

00:50:40.080 --> 00:50:44.550
in historical society, which is
derided as dreamy but important

00:50:44.550 --> 00:50:45.720
repository.

00:50:45.720 --> 00:50:48.450
And we know that
it was in the West.

00:50:48.450 --> 00:50:51.360
It was started very much
with the Unitarians,

00:50:51.360 --> 00:50:55.560
the theosophists, new age
spirituality, and so on.

00:50:55.560 --> 00:50:57.870
And as I've discussed,
in North America,

00:50:57.870 --> 00:51:00.720
ecological spirituality
John Thoreau--

00:51:00.720 --> 00:51:04.260
I mean, Thoreau's
spirit insights

00:51:04.260 --> 00:51:05.850
were carried
particularly by people

00:51:05.850 --> 00:51:08.980
like John Miller, Aldo
Leopold, of course,

00:51:08.980 --> 00:51:12.036
Rachel Carsons, and all
those people [INAUDIBLE]..

00:51:12.036 --> 00:51:15.180
And today has emerged as
a significant American

00:51:15.180 --> 00:51:18.780
environmental movement, although
it has many different branches.

00:51:18.780 --> 00:51:20.760
And you already begin
to see the hook up

00:51:20.760 --> 00:51:23.880
with Asian
environmentalists thought

00:51:23.880 --> 00:51:28.440
and proto-environmentalists
thought with American Buddhists

00:51:28.440 --> 00:51:29.560
and others, right?

00:51:29.560 --> 00:51:33.680
Like Gary Snyder, Alan
Watts, and others.

00:51:33.680 --> 00:51:36.600
Today, modern associational
groups and circles

00:51:36.600 --> 00:51:39.000
have also grown in Asia,
Latin America, and Africa,

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:40.980
who seek to protect
the environment

00:51:40.980 --> 00:51:43.110
and join with the
people who are really

00:51:43.110 --> 00:51:46.800
most immediately and
most powerfully affected

00:51:46.800 --> 00:51:48.330
by climate change.

00:51:48.330 --> 00:51:51.700
That is marginal indigenous
traditional communities

00:51:51.700 --> 00:51:54.810
who have been bearing the brunt
of the ecological devastation

00:51:54.810 --> 00:51:56.310
of the world.

00:51:56.310 --> 00:52:00.805
These marginal communities often
tend to view nature as sacred.

00:52:00.805 --> 00:52:04.260
Though not necessarily, we
shouldn't romanticize them,

00:52:04.260 --> 00:52:07.980
but they often need to view it
as sacred in order to preserve

00:52:07.980 --> 00:52:09.990
what they have, the
little that they have .

00:52:09.990 --> 00:52:11.480
And they often use--

00:52:11.480 --> 00:52:16.110
and they employ the
psychology to protect it.

00:52:16.110 --> 00:52:18.630
If you look at tree-hugging
movements and so on,

00:52:18.630 --> 00:52:23.220
these have very much to do with
their local notions of what

00:52:23.220 --> 00:52:24.120
nature is about.

00:52:24.120 --> 00:52:27.150
And the biggest environmental
movement in India

00:52:27.150 --> 00:52:28.800
took off with the
Cziko movement,

00:52:28.800 --> 00:52:31.980
which is a tree-hugging hugging
movement of 1972, right?

00:52:31.980 --> 00:52:37.190
And spawned a huge
movement from there.

00:52:37.190 --> 00:52:39.660
I mean this kind of alliance
is not just happening

00:52:39.660 --> 00:52:41.890
in the developing world.

00:52:41.890 --> 00:52:44.620
And I will give you an
example of the Dakota Access

00:52:44.620 --> 00:52:48.250
Pipeline, which could
have had a huge impact.

00:52:48.250 --> 00:52:54.760
Until, I think it was January,
the Army Reserve Corps

00:52:54.760 --> 00:52:58.990
of Engineers had agreed that
this will not take place

00:52:58.990 --> 00:53:01.240
in this Dakota country, right?

00:53:01.240 --> 00:53:03.730
And it was only with
the new president,

00:53:03.730 --> 00:53:06.750
with that unnamed
president, who--

00:53:06.750 --> 00:53:08.140
were this was reversed.

00:53:08.140 --> 00:53:11.140
So if it had been
pursued, it could

00:53:11.140 --> 00:53:12.940
have had a rolling effect.

00:53:12.940 --> 00:53:14.050
I think it's set back now.

00:53:14.050 --> 00:53:15.633
I don't think it's
going to disappear.

00:53:15.633 --> 00:53:19.620
But you did have a lot of
people mobilize around it.

00:53:23.250 --> 00:53:26.720
And there's a lot of indigenous
symbolism and sort of nature,

00:53:26.720 --> 00:53:29.030
sacristy, and so on
going on here as well.

00:53:31.560 --> 00:53:35.040
Now, within the
Asian traditions,

00:53:35.040 --> 00:53:38.180
we have theologically an Indic,
Chinese, and indigenous peoples

00:53:38.180 --> 00:53:39.320
cosmology.

00:53:39.320 --> 00:53:42.350
The sacredness of nature
is of course a byproduct

00:53:42.350 --> 00:53:46.640
of a perspective integrating
social moral and natural order,

00:53:46.640 --> 00:53:49.060
what in Chinese is
known as tianren

00:53:49.060 --> 00:53:51.740
heyi, the organic unity.

00:53:51.740 --> 00:53:55.940
And this is of course
now something that has--

00:53:55.940 --> 00:53:58.490
that was forgotten for
the last 100 years,

00:53:58.490 --> 00:54:01.460
but it's coming back
in a big way not least

00:54:01.460 --> 00:54:04.160
due to some of Professor
Puett's efforts

00:54:04.160 --> 00:54:08.270
I'm sure, since he has
such an impact on the most

00:54:08.270 --> 00:54:13.630
impactful class in the US.

00:54:13.630 --> 00:54:19.280
So but also I should say that
John and Mary Evelyn have left,

00:54:19.280 --> 00:54:23.090
but this whole religion,
the whole study

00:54:23.090 --> 00:54:25.670
of religion and environment,
begins at Harvard

00:54:25.670 --> 00:54:29.090
with Mary Ellen Tucker
and John Graham, who

00:54:29.090 --> 00:54:35.910
produce the 10 volumes of world
religions and the environment,

00:54:35.910 --> 00:54:37.010
right?

00:54:37.010 --> 00:54:40.130
In the 90s, I think it was.

00:54:40.130 --> 00:54:43.060
So they were really ahead
of their time in many ways.

00:54:43.060 --> 00:54:46.280
What draws these divers
currents and phenomena is

00:54:46.280 --> 00:54:50.840
their anti-dualism, the
idea that you cannot have

00:54:50.840 --> 00:54:54.110
an integrated and organic
view, cannot operate

00:54:54.110 --> 00:54:58.580
on the assumption that humans
and nature are a binary,

00:54:58.580 --> 00:55:02.690
that humans can in fact
conquer nature as something.

00:55:02.690 --> 00:55:05.790
And rather see nature is
very much part of yourself.

00:55:05.790 --> 00:55:09.230
I'm sure you heard a lot
about this in your discussions

00:55:09.230 --> 00:55:13.290
here before, so I won't
bore you with those details.

00:55:13.290 --> 00:55:17.700
But I do have lots
of examples here,

00:55:17.700 --> 00:55:22.800
which I don't think we need to
go into since time is short.

00:55:22.800 --> 00:55:26.400
But one of the very
important activists

00:55:26.400 --> 00:55:29.250
in all these Asian
religions are in fact

00:55:29.250 --> 00:55:35.730
the Thai Cambodian
Laotian Buddhist monks.

00:55:35.730 --> 00:55:37.830
These are forest
monks who have--

00:55:37.830 --> 00:55:41.190
I've been spending a lot of
time with the Cambodian monks

00:55:41.190 --> 00:55:44.490
and the local communities who
have now sort of taken over

00:55:44.490 --> 00:55:45.150
from the monks.

00:55:45.150 --> 00:55:47.700
The monks are also
still very important,

00:55:47.700 --> 00:55:51.870
as they have this ceremony
of ordinating trees, right?

00:55:51.870 --> 00:55:55.590
And the ceremonial
role being of trees

00:55:55.590 --> 00:56:00.570
and so on, which has unleashed
a very powerful movement

00:56:00.570 --> 00:56:05.940
against deforestation and dam
building in those regions.

00:56:05.940 --> 00:56:09.310
And the Thai Buddhist monk
Bhikku Buddhadasa, of course,

00:56:09.310 --> 00:56:10.250
puts it very simply.

00:56:10.250 --> 00:56:12.480
He says once--
the way he relates

00:56:12.480 --> 00:56:15.810
it is that one's realization
of the interconnected

00:56:15.810 --> 00:56:19.450
of all-- interconnectedness
of all things in life forms,

00:56:19.450 --> 00:56:21.420
which are transient
and changeable,

00:56:21.420 --> 00:56:23.670
will help deflate
one's ego, knowing

00:56:23.670 --> 00:56:25.560
that everyone is
one and the same,

00:56:25.560 --> 00:56:28.740
being subject to the
same natural laws.

00:56:28.740 --> 00:56:31.350
His spirituality rejected
specific religious

00:56:31.350 --> 00:56:32.160
identification.

00:56:32.160 --> 00:56:35.670
He was very much the
spirituality mode,

00:56:35.670 --> 00:56:37.810
this non institutionalized
religion,

00:56:37.810 --> 00:56:41.610
this de-institutionalized
notion of something spiritual.

00:56:41.610 --> 00:56:44.190
And he was one of the
most important, I think,

00:56:44.190 --> 00:56:47.100
inspirations for the forest
monk environmental movements.

00:56:47.100 --> 00:56:51.030
The other place that this
is very important is Taiwan.

00:56:51.030 --> 00:56:54.420
Taiwan has one of the most
dynamic civil societies in Asia

00:56:54.420 --> 00:56:55.480
today.

00:56:55.480 --> 00:56:59.130
And within that, the Buddhist
groups are very powerful.

00:56:59.130 --> 00:57:01.230
You all heard of Ciji,
but there's Fagu,

00:57:01.230 --> 00:57:02.510
there's Foguan [INAUDIBLE].

00:57:02.510 --> 00:57:04.360
There are many others.

00:57:04.360 --> 00:57:08.340
And all of them have as
one of the central planks,

00:57:08.340 --> 00:57:11.040
the central plank in
most, one vow, which

00:57:11.040 --> 00:57:13.560
is protect the environment.

00:57:13.560 --> 00:57:16.330
And you may have individual
critiques of what they do

00:57:16.330 --> 00:57:18.690
or what they don't and
how much they give in

00:57:18.690 --> 00:57:20.730
and how much they don't,
but there are also

00:57:20.730 --> 00:57:24.840
some very powerful thinkers
among some of these.

00:57:24.840 --> 00:57:28.790
I have worked on one
or two of them as well.

00:57:28.790 --> 00:57:33.780
So, and anyway, there's
a lot more here.

00:57:33.780 --> 00:57:35.870
I don't think we need
to go into all of this.

00:57:35.870 --> 00:57:38.960
But I do want to sort of try
and understand-- try and see

00:57:38.960 --> 00:57:42.920
how we can understand the
relationship of these religions

00:57:42.920 --> 00:57:46.632
to this, what is ultimately
a new project, right?

00:57:46.632 --> 00:57:47.840
The Environmental Protection.

00:57:47.840 --> 00:57:50.040
You can say that Daoism
is interested in nature.

00:57:50.040 --> 00:57:53.510
Therefore, it's a
smooth, continuous flow.

00:57:53.510 --> 00:57:55.760
So we really have
to change our notion

00:57:55.760 --> 00:57:57.410
of historical understanding.

00:57:57.410 --> 00:58:00.470
It's not one of
substantial transition

00:58:00.470 --> 00:58:03.470
from the substance of one thing
to a substance of another.

00:58:03.470 --> 00:58:05.840
It's if we look at it from
the philosophical idea

00:58:05.840 --> 00:58:10.250
of emergence, then
you know that when

00:58:10.250 --> 00:58:14.180
a historical event or process
impacts the social formation,

00:58:14.180 --> 00:58:16.970
it effects an emergence which
combines both the prevailing

00:58:16.970 --> 00:58:18.680
factor and the new thing.

00:58:18.680 --> 00:58:20.630
But the interesting
historical problem

00:58:20.630 --> 00:58:24.800
is that the new phenomenon
seeks to justify itself only

00:58:24.800 --> 00:58:26.810
in terms of the old, right?

00:58:26.810 --> 00:58:30.230
So this is the narrative
challenging, as it

00:58:30.230 --> 00:58:33.220
were, the circulation, right?

00:58:33.220 --> 00:58:36.290
And I think that we've
had-- all of deconstruction

00:58:36.290 --> 00:58:39.350
has been based on this,
the separation, right?

00:58:39.350 --> 00:58:40.670
Your claim.

00:58:40.670 --> 00:58:42.740
And I think we should
really go beyond that

00:58:42.740 --> 00:58:45.500
and recognize, with people
like Paul Ricoeur and so on,

00:58:45.500 --> 00:58:48.020
that the important
thing is the pertinence.

00:58:48.020 --> 00:58:50.210
If these people feel
impelled to do something,

00:58:50.210 --> 00:58:51.770
that is a good cause, right?

00:58:51.770 --> 00:58:54.230
And they connected with
something that they can see

00:58:54.230 --> 00:58:56.030
was there, then that's
good enough, right?

00:58:56.030 --> 00:58:58.070
What is the pertinence,
and does the permanence

00:58:58.070 --> 00:59:00.510
have persuasive power?

00:59:00.510 --> 00:59:05.150
So I think this is something
very important, that.

00:59:05.150 --> 00:59:07.460
And here I just
want to talk about,

00:59:07.460 --> 00:59:12.260
and I'm also indebted once
again to Mary Evelyn for this,

00:59:12.260 --> 00:59:15.350
Pope Francis's June
2015 encyclical

00:59:15.350 --> 00:59:17.245
on care for our common home.

00:59:17.245 --> 00:59:19.370
This is a very radical
document, and likely to have

00:59:19.370 --> 00:59:20.810
a huge impact,
because it's going

00:59:20.810 --> 00:59:22.830
to be thought in all
the Catholic schools

00:59:22.830 --> 00:59:24.510
around the world.

00:59:24.510 --> 00:59:28.580
And which integrates
ecology and justice.

00:59:28.580 --> 00:59:31.760
And it's very radical,
because popes earlier had

00:59:31.760 --> 00:59:35.150
made kind of environmental
noises earlier,

00:59:35.150 --> 00:59:39.170
but they stayed within the
framework of the stewardship

00:59:39.170 --> 00:59:39.770
argument.

00:59:39.770 --> 00:59:42.200
Now, those of you who are
in environmental humanities

00:59:42.200 --> 00:59:45.110
would be familiar with
Lynn White's critique

00:59:45.110 --> 00:59:48.590
of Christianity as
something that sees nature

00:59:48.590 --> 00:59:51.170
as something given by God
to humans to do whatever

00:59:51.170 --> 00:59:52.280
you like with it, right?

00:59:52.280 --> 00:59:55.970
For your bounty.

00:59:55.970 --> 01:00:01.760
And the response of the church
to that kind of critique

01:00:01.760 --> 01:00:05.090
is that while God gave it to
humans to be a steward of,

01:00:05.090 --> 01:00:06.200
to steward it, right?

01:00:06.200 --> 01:00:10.490
So there's still a duality,
but it's one of care.

01:00:10.490 --> 01:00:14.690
And what this pope
does is that he

01:00:14.690 --> 01:00:19.580
does refer, for various
reasons, to many earlier pope's

01:00:19.580 --> 01:00:21.890
statements and things
that-- but he's changing

01:00:21.890 --> 01:00:23.540
the underlying argument.

01:00:23.540 --> 01:00:25.880
It's not about
stewardship or anything.

01:00:25.880 --> 01:00:30.170
It is tied very much on a
very different concept of what

01:00:30.170 --> 01:00:32.360
is the divine will, right?

01:00:32.360 --> 01:00:35.120
He's talking about-- he
invokes Mother Earth,

01:00:35.120 --> 01:00:37.940
he invokes Francis of Assisi.

01:00:37.940 --> 01:00:41.900
And he really refers
to integral ecology,

01:00:41.900 --> 01:00:43.870
connecting humans
to the environment,

01:00:43.870 --> 01:00:46.700
and to the evolutionary
process, right?

01:00:46.700 --> 01:00:48.560
So he's making these
radical changes

01:00:48.560 --> 01:00:51.470
framed within of course a
hermeneutic tradition, which

01:00:51.470 --> 01:00:52.994
he has to.

01:00:52.994 --> 01:00:55.160
But it really gives you the
sense of the pertinence.

01:00:55.160 --> 01:00:56.540
Is it pertinent or not?

01:00:56.540 --> 01:00:58.160
How is it going to be accepted?

01:00:58.160 --> 01:00:58.730
And how long?

01:00:58.730 --> 01:01:00.560
We don't know how long
this pope will last.

01:01:00.560 --> 01:01:03.750
But there are many forces
working against him.

01:01:03.750 --> 01:01:05.360
But I think he's
turning out to be

01:01:05.360 --> 01:01:09.930
one of the most interesting
figures of our time.

01:01:09.930 --> 01:01:14.040
Of course, we've talked also
about India and the Hindu

01:01:14.040 --> 01:01:16.200
groups that are
fashioning themselves also

01:01:16.200 --> 01:01:17.825
in this response.

01:01:17.825 --> 01:01:19.200
Of course, here
there's a problem

01:01:19.200 --> 01:01:23.220
that you get Hindu poulsbo mixed
in with the Hindu naturalism

01:01:23.220 --> 01:01:23.760
and so on.

01:01:23.760 --> 01:01:26.970
But those are one of the
problems that we also have.

01:01:26.970 --> 01:01:29.910
I talked about Taiwan.

01:01:29.910 --> 01:01:32.010
So these religious
groups in Asia

01:01:32.010 --> 01:01:34.200
may be particularly
suited to mediate

01:01:34.200 --> 01:01:37.510
between precarious
local communities

01:01:37.510 --> 01:01:41.370
and this transcendence
of sustainability.

01:01:41.370 --> 01:01:43.110
In many parts of
Asia, communities

01:01:43.110 --> 01:01:45.360
are resisting efforts to
exploit or industrialize

01:01:45.360 --> 01:01:48.450
their natural resources, but
appealing to the security

01:01:48.450 --> 01:01:49.960
of commons, right?

01:01:49.960 --> 01:01:52.800
Daoism, animism, Buddhism,
Christianity, Hinduism

01:01:52.800 --> 01:01:57.080
are utilized to protect
resources by using terminology

01:01:57.080 --> 01:01:59.040
in China of shantou, right?

01:01:59.040 --> 01:02:00.720
These are sort of
sacred home lands,

01:02:00.720 --> 01:02:02.580
sacred groves, the hope--

01:02:02.580 --> 01:02:05.220
whole segments of Yunnan
are now considered

01:02:05.220 --> 01:02:09.210
to be sacred forests of
marginal peoples and so on.

01:02:09.210 --> 01:02:12.390
Community forests, holy
water, especially in India,

01:02:12.390 --> 01:02:16.200
to oppose local environmental
pollution now, apparently.

01:02:16.200 --> 01:02:19.170
Talking about the environment,
the legal underpinnings,

01:02:19.170 --> 01:02:21.060
the Ganges polluted as it is.

01:02:21.060 --> 01:02:23.990
One of the most polluted
rivers probably in the world.

01:02:23.990 --> 01:02:30.090
As now, it's now considered
to be a crime, a legal crime

01:02:30.090 --> 01:02:30.675
to pollute.

01:02:30.675 --> 01:02:31.800
And no-- what is it called?

01:02:31.800 --> 01:02:35.160
The Ganges is considered to be
the equivalent of a person, has

01:02:35.160 --> 01:02:36.760
the rights of a person.

01:02:36.760 --> 01:02:39.840
So you can be charged
for killing it, right?

01:02:39.840 --> 01:02:41.600
So you can get that
kind of sentence.

01:02:41.600 --> 01:02:43.141
And this of course,
in Latin America,

01:02:43.141 --> 01:02:45.840
you have a lot of these
countries with trees and so on.

01:02:45.840 --> 01:02:48.270
So I think there is a
kind of legal underpinning

01:02:48.270 --> 01:02:53.940
to this idea of the sacristy
of natural creatures,

01:02:53.940 --> 01:02:55.850
I should say.

01:02:55.850 --> 01:02:57.960
And I've talked about
several of these.

01:02:57.960 --> 01:03:02.130
Here is a conference I did in,
just two or three months ago,

01:03:02.130 --> 01:03:03.750
in Phnom Penh.

01:03:03.750 --> 01:03:05.730
And where it was
really exciting,

01:03:05.730 --> 01:03:08.700
because you could see
although it was started

01:03:08.700 --> 01:03:11.392
by these [INAUDIBLE] group,
a [INAUDIBLE] and there

01:03:11.392 --> 01:03:12.850
are two or three
different forests.

01:03:12.850 --> 01:03:18.870
Bihar, [INAUDIBLE],, these
were forest dwellers,

01:03:18.870 --> 01:03:23.340
semi sort of Cambodian
and semi tribal.

01:03:23.340 --> 01:03:25.350
They were Hindu Buddhist.

01:03:25.350 --> 01:03:27.750
And they took on the movement.

01:03:27.750 --> 01:03:30.300
And once they started
digging on the movement,

01:03:30.300 --> 01:03:31.860
the Buddhists joined them.

01:03:31.860 --> 01:03:33.810
And then local civil
society joined them.

01:03:33.810 --> 01:03:37.290
And it became so
prominent that it got

01:03:37.290 --> 01:03:39.750
the attention of global media.

01:03:39.750 --> 01:03:41.940
And suddenly, it
became a place where

01:03:41.940 --> 01:03:47.010
all levels of civil society
began to enter there.

01:03:47.010 --> 01:03:49.890
So there were-- they
set up very articulate.

01:03:49.890 --> 01:03:56.760
At this particular-- this monk
to your right, by the way,

01:03:56.760 --> 01:03:58.240
he's in--

01:03:58.240 --> 01:03:59.160
I have his name.

01:03:59.160 --> 01:04:01.340
Venerable Ben Solute, I think.

01:04:01.340 --> 01:04:04.020
He's at UVA, this guy.

01:04:04.020 --> 01:04:05.340
Very articulate.

01:04:05.340 --> 01:04:08.190
He spent a lot of time in
India, so he speaks English.

01:04:08.190 --> 01:04:11.700
And he is very interesting.

01:04:11.700 --> 01:04:15.060
The other guy is
probably, but he's--

01:04:15.060 --> 01:04:17.562
he says I talk to
[INAUDIBLE] all the time.

01:04:17.562 --> 01:04:19.770
You don't want to go too
close to a person like that.

01:04:19.770 --> 01:04:22.560
But the other guy, he
doesn't speak English,

01:04:22.560 --> 01:04:25.230
but he seems to be much more--

01:04:25.230 --> 01:04:27.070
with much greater integrity.

01:04:27.070 --> 01:04:31.550
Anyway, he won't
talk to [INAUDIBLE]..

01:04:31.550 --> 01:04:33.820
Here are some of the pictures.

01:04:33.820 --> 01:04:36.510
This is also from
the cover of my book.

01:04:36.510 --> 01:04:40.170
This is a very-- this are
these, this group that has been

01:04:40.170 --> 01:04:43.260
demonstrating since I think 20--

01:04:43.260 --> 01:04:44.730
long before 2010.

01:04:44.730 --> 01:04:47.790
But they got-- came
to attention in 2011.

01:04:47.790 --> 01:04:51.390
What they're doing, they call
themselves Cambodia's avatars.

01:04:51.390 --> 01:04:54.060
And for them, avatar has a
meaning in the Hindu Buddhist

01:04:54.060 --> 01:04:55.890
tradition.

01:04:55.890 --> 01:05:00.450
And what they did is they began
to lead weekly demonstrations

01:05:00.450 --> 01:05:05.010
in the main square in Phnom
Penh, where they would engage

01:05:05.010 --> 01:05:08.560
in their own forms of ritual
theaters of protest, right?

01:05:08.560 --> 01:05:09.910
So it will be something.

01:05:09.910 --> 01:05:11.790
It would be ritualized.

01:05:11.790 --> 01:05:13.020
It would be theatrical.

01:05:13.020 --> 01:05:14.010
But it was a petition.

01:05:14.010 --> 01:05:16.380
It was their form of protests.

01:05:16.380 --> 01:05:18.840
And it attracted
so much attention.

01:05:18.840 --> 01:05:20.970
And they took on
the name avatar,

01:05:20.970 --> 01:05:25.980
but not because of their local
meaning, but because the movie.

01:05:25.980 --> 01:05:33.180
So they're depicting themselves
as this creature below, right?

01:05:33.180 --> 01:05:36.401
So that is what this
whole thing is all about.

01:05:36.401 --> 01:05:38.900
But that's a very interesting
aspect of circulatory history,

01:05:38.900 --> 01:05:42.510
where it comes back again to
you but via the global media,

01:05:42.510 --> 01:05:43.410
right?

01:05:43.410 --> 01:05:46.119
And they got huge global
attention on this.

01:05:46.119 --> 01:05:48.660
And I think there are several
people, several groups that are

01:05:48.660 --> 01:05:49.929
studying the impact of avatar.

01:05:49.929 --> 01:05:51.720
I don't know if they
started studying this.

01:05:51.720 --> 01:05:53.465
I don't think those
two have been joined.

01:05:53.465 --> 01:05:57.330
It's a good cultural
studies project.

01:05:57.330 --> 01:05:59.490
I met several of these people.

